      • signUp

        <any> signUp(java.lang.String username,
             java.lang.String password,
             AuthSignUpOptions options)
        Creates a new user account with the specified username and password. Can also pass in user attributes to associate with the user through the options object.
        Parameters:
        username - A login identifier e.g. `superdog22`; or an email/phone number, depending on configuration
        password - The user's password
        options - Advanced options such as additional attributes of the user or validation data
        Returns:
        An Rx Single which emits an AuthSignUpResult on success, or an AuthException on failure

      • confirmSignUp

        <any> confirmSignUp(java.lang.String username,
                    java.lang.String confirmationCode)
        If you have attribute confirmation enabled, this will allow the user to enter the confirmation code they received to activate their account.
        Parameters:
        username - A login identifier e.g. `superdog22`; or an email/phone number, depending on configuration
        confirmationCode - The confirmation code the user received
        Returns:
        An Rx Single which emits an AuthSignUpResult on successful confirmation, or an AuthException on failure

      • signIn

        <any> signIn(java.lang.String username,
             java.lang.String password,
             AuthSignInOptions options)
        Basic authentication to the app with a username and password or, if custom auth is setup, you can send null for those and the necessary authentication details in the options object.
        Parameters:
        username - A login identifier e.g. `superdog22`; or an email/phone number, depending on configuration
        password - User's password for normal signup, null if custom auth or passwordless configurations are setup
        options - Advanced options such as a map of auth information for custom auth
        Returns:
        An Rx Single which emits AuthSignInResult on success, AuthException on failure

      • fetchAuthSession

        <any> fetchAuthSession()
        Retrieve the user's current session information - by default just whether they are signed out or in. Depending on how a plugin implements this, the resulting AuthSession can also be cast to a type specific to that plugin which contains the various security tokens and other identifying information if you want to manually use them outside the plugin. Within Amplify this should not be needed as the other categories will automatically work as long as you are signed in.
        Returns:
        An Rx Single which emits AuthSession on success, AuthException on failure

        newPassword - The new password desired on the user account
